segments.text: How did you all feel about him?
He became dean in the 50s.
What kind of a dean was he?
We were concerned he was good.
I agree.
I agree.
See, Margaret worked for him.
Really?
Oh.
Oh, she worked for him.
Was he a good person to work for?
Yeah.
But she had a... She'd been in so many different things
And she was a gal that wouldn't back off for anything.
And she'd come home and say, Dean Benson, and they had a fight, the big boys, Dean Benson and the boys that were running the, what do you call it, where they,
My memory is from then.
And they had a big fight in there one time, and she was telling me about it.
And he, and Dean Benson came out of that room just red, Cumberston.
The other guy left.
Cajon.
Cajon, they were fighting.
And he left.
Dean came out of there.
And Margaret said her office was like this, like the doors over there.
And they had a chair right here.
And he plopped himself down in that chair.
And I'd given Margaret some of her little old cars.
And she had one of them in the drawer.
And she says, Dean, do you want to see my new automobile?
And so she reached in the drawer and pulled it out and put it in the run of him.
And he broke up laughing.
She was that way.
She could settle him down.
That's what she was after.
And if I could chat with her, would she say positive things about Fred Benson?
Yes.
She had a high regard for him.
Some of those employees she had up there, she didn't like.
Now, where was the dean's office?
It was in the engineering building on that end, on the second floor up there.
When Earl Rudder was selected as the new president of Texas A&M, what did you and the other people here on the campus think?
We didn't pay any attention to it.
You see, my father had told me about so much about this faculty, that all these people were in here that didn't have that background.
Mm-hmm.
And they were fighting and killing each other.
Just climbing up a ladder.
If you could knock them off a ladder, so be it.
And I just sat back and laughed at them.
I had a boss named Vestal.
And he was a hard hitter.
But I knew what was going to happen.
They'll just fight themselves to pieces, and few of them will win.
But most of them will leave and go somewhere else.
Now, in the 50s, where did you and your family live?
In the 50s, I built my home out in North Oakwood.
In North Oakwood.
I built that in 46, and I still live in there.
And on what street?
College View Street.
What did it cost?
Do you remember what it cost per square foot to build it?
It cost about, the total thing I think was about $8,000.
And it stood the time.
It was still, it hadn't cracked or anything.
It's got 57 yards of concrete in that slab.
And the NM Consolidated School was right there convenient for your children.
No, we were on Bryan.
Oh, I'm sorry.
You said North Oakwood.
I was thinking of South Oakwood.
North Oakwood, yeah.
We had to wait until they paid.
We had a fight on that.
The Crockett School.
Mary had to walk down that thing and cross that
How new was North Oakwood when you built your house?
Were there many houses in it?
There were a few in there, but they were all built prior to World War II.
In the block I was in, there are
There were two there and three there.
There were three houses in there.
Ours was the fourth one and the fifth one was built about 1950.
So they're trying to sell it at $129,000.
If you and your wife and your friends were going to go out
for entertainment in the 50s.
Where did you go?
Oh, the college put on a lot of things.
They were good about that sort of thing.
Oh, you went to the Skyway.
The Skyway drive-in?
Drive-ins were big.
You could carry your kids with you and everything else.
Did y'all go much downtown to the movie?
Yes, we went to the movies.
Where would you have gone out to eat?
We went to Hotard's.
At Hotard's?
Downtown.
And we trained our children that once they got through that door at Hotard's, they didn't make any, carry on any fuss.
They would behave.
They behaved.
Were you all churchgoers in the 50s?
Oh, yeah.
Where?
First Presbyterian Church of College Station.
We got in a big fight with Dean Boulder.
And we wanted to fire Dr. Anderson, the preacher.
We thought it was time we went in.
Because I think y'all were going there when we got here in 59 and I think y'all were in that church then.
Yeah.
We got here just after the new building opened.
Yes, sir.
The old one was still standing when we got here in September of 59 but the services were being held in the new building.
Yeah, you see, another thing, I had a business on the side, Scotts Industries.
I realized that we didn't have any printing, blueprinting for engineers here.
We all had to send it to Austin or Houston or Waco.
About that time, in about 1946, Oculus came on with a new machine, and I bought it.
And where did you open that business?
In my garage.
All right, when it outgrew that, where did you locate it?
It's on Old Southern Spring Road.
That building's got that big billboard in the front of it.
So that's where you started?
Really?
After you left the garage, where it is now?
Yeah.
Now, when did you leave A&M?
In 60.
We used to run that thing for a long time.
The only thing we really made money on was, you didn't make much money on what came over the counter except for people like Codell, Ralph, and Scott.
When you printed a job for them, it usually cost them about four or five grand.
And that's when you made your money.
And you'd make one of those about every year.
And so I never, one of the things I did, I never involved myself as a professional engineer.
except in my own business, which was airfoil.
I started airfoil in 60.
Airfoil Impellers.
A-I-R-F-O-I-L?
Impellers Incorporated.
It's over on over in the industrial fire
right next to the power plant over there.
And Brian.
And Brian.
And so that just grew, and so that kept me busy.
So I finally quit A&M in 1960.
All right, and your wife worked how long out here?
I don't know.
She also, first thing she did in 1960, she
She was, we made her postmaster's bride.
And we were Republicans.
Took us a long time to do it, but the one that really, really warped it up was, what were we talking about the other, he was, he was the one
But it was J.W.
Hall that got it for us.
He was big in the Republican Party.
Who were the other key Republicans in Brazos County in the 50s, 60s?
Well, all the people except for
ones we called Yellow Dog Democrats.
Yellow Dog Democrats.
Those are the liberals.
And there were about 10% of all the people in Texas were among those.
But the Democrat Party, the people that were in there and voting,
were Republicans in nature.
Oh, I know.
But who were the key leaders in this county that were Republicans early on?
J.W.
Hall, myself, and later on it was, what's the name of the bookstore man?
Leupold?
Well, Leupold was the one that kept us from getting Thomas' appointment.
And she didn't have it very long.
Of course, then Kennedy went out, so they went back and moved with him.
He was a Democrat.
And so that's where we were kind of out in the cold.
There's a little story about that.
John Tower came down here on one of his trips down here as a Republican.
And he flew into Easterwood Field.
And so, oh.
They asked us to go out and so he'd have some people to speak to, you know, to stop and tell us what he was going to do.
So we did.
And when the newspaper reported that, he said,
They labeled off some of the people that were there and said a small group, including a Babes in Arms.
You know who that Babes in Arms was?
Your grandchild?
No, my son.
Oh.
Well, our youngest son.
Oh.
James.
But how old was he?
He was just as young as that.
That was in 60.
Oh, okay, okay.
Mama was older than me.
We had gone out there to the help tower, you know, try to get a little, and then we had a lot of meetings and
I remember one of them, I was talking to George Bush, who ran for governor.
He and I stood out on the side of that building over there at the American Legion for about two hours just talking to each other.
That's the first Georgian.
What was your impression of him then?
Good.
See, I was the precinct chairman for 11 for 30 some odd years.
Who was the first important Republican to win a local office here?
Do you remember?
Would that be up in the 60s or 70s?
It probably would be.
because they were all Democrats back there.
But still, what they said and what they did was exactly what the Republicans are doing today.
They're at heart, they're really Republicans.
But they're all what we call closet Republicans.
And we go ask, like, the president of the bank, or the president of the big company.
He was a closet Republican.
He'd give you some money, but you didn't say nothing about it.
You just wouldn't use it.
I mean, we're talking closeted Republicans.
All right, I believe we can kind of bring this to a conclusion now.
Trying to summarize all of your A&M relations, what did you learn in all of the years you were associated with A&M that was important in your life?
What did it mean to you to have an A&M connection?
The engineering background I got.
And what I could do with it afterwards.
And it was a good background?
Yeah.
And when I worked for A&M, I was someone over there that people sought out.
Was the Texas A&M engineering, was it theoretical or was it applied?
It was applied.
Problem solving, real world.
They always came after me.
I mean, J.W.
Sorensen was one of my classmates.
He was always after me.
And what I know, and I've known this for a long time, for about 60-some odd years, fan business is a real...
You got simple engineering in it, and it's just as straightforward as you can be.
But for some reason or another, engineers just don't like it.
And this computer came on, and that saved me an awful lot of trouble.
That thing there.
What creates this Aggie pride and spirit?
Why are Aggies so proud?
Because the relationship they have with other people is one of the things.
But they've always had, well, their athletics has been up and straight and always good.

you never outside of that thing that happened in Baylor I don't know of any other place they behaved themselves when they went off and that thing in Baylor was all Baylor it wasn't A&M but I think the biggest thing was when the old time stuff when they marched in there at

on company front and they were all in there at one time or they were coming out and then they had you had you had supervision from army people now I think that's one of the best things we can have in a school now I'm in the alliance club and we've had two men in the alliance club that
that were operating the ones in Bryan High School.
And what I saw those men do with those kids, I appreciated it.
Because they knew, the kids knew that there was a certain discipline that they had to get down.
And so that's one of the things.
And I hate to, I'm glad the Corps is still here.
and I think it ought to be in almost all of the big high schools.
We wouldn't be, they wouldn't be hauling guns in there.
If you were a hired consultant to Texas A&M's leadership now, the decision makers about this institution, what would you advise them to do with A&M in the future?
is Millen College.
I mean, get other colleges and institutions.
I mean, not colleges, but out of high school.
The transition from high school into an institution like this, an ordinary man can't handle it.
But if you can put him in an institution like,

uh blend college they're doing one hell of a job i saw it with my son they just start to blossom how how big should a m's enrollment be allowed to grow 50 grand you think we could handle that many students i think you can but i i would i would take a and m and uh
Of course, we've got Glenn, which I think is enough right here, but they're going to have to be others.
But you've got to have them up against, well, like Brenham is a good organization there.
There's theirs there.
But all of the big institutions have got to do this the same way.
You've got to have them come out of high school, then you've got to have them go into some sort of a,
junior college, what I call it, and have those very well-regulated and top-flight employees, or professors.
It's just important to put the best man there and have him here at A&M.
And another thing, they're all uptight about this
that the professors should do research on.
I'm not in favor of that.
I agree with you.
I want them to teach.
Get down with the students and they, now if they can change that from have student activities that is
Professors should have, he'd teach a class for many hours here, but I want him over here in some sort of activity that's helping them learn what he taught them.
Right?
Now, I can show you this.
Texas Tech has this thing.
I'm interested in this safe room for tornadoes.
And they have a big thing with the FINA people.
But they required all those people, and they sent me a list of them with their little piddling things, unconnected.
Now, there's got to be some, you've got to teach these
professors to teach the people to look at stuff.
And the second thing is you never quit reading and studying.
I can tell you, if you're interested in mechanics like that, take Popular Mechanics and Popular Science, read them from cover to cover.
And also, you can get a lot of engineering books.
I spent many hours over here in- In the Enging Library?
No, not the Enging Library.
Oh.
The regular library.
In Cushing.
Cushing.
And that big old room up there, I'd sit there many hours.
And what I was doing, I was trying to change a V8 Ford into a front-wheel drive.

If you could make a major gift to Texas A&M, somebody walked up to you and gave you a check for a million dollars, but you have to pass it on to A&M, but you decide how the money will be spent, what would you want A&M to do with a gift that you made?
What would you want it for?
What in ag engineering?
Students, faculty, research?
No, mainly students and faculty that are conscious of, well, it amounts to the fluid mechanics, the air.
I'm a fan man.
I'm sitting here and I know more about fans than anybody in the country.
I can tell you that and I can back it up.
You want somebody to continue that?
Continue that, work at it, and I've got
I've got equipment in my shop out here that won't be built for 10 years.
My, my, how good, how good.
I mean, because the price of energy is too low.
I mean, that's, and you've got to get people, you've got to train these people to look at things and sit and study them.
And then they've got to help.
It's a marvelous field in health.
All right, my last question.
What feelings do you carry in your heart today for Texas A&M?
How do you feel about A&M today?
Well, it's a great institution.
That's all I can say about it.
People can come here, and if they apply themselves, and according to what they tell them,
They'll survive.
Now, you may not end up in what you set out to do as your own thing, but you can follow it along and do the very best you can, and you'll be rewarded for it.
Are you grateful your dad got hired here in 1919?
Oh, yeah.
I'm sorry he didn't live, but that's, that's, that's the roll of the dice.
He wound up the, the cancer had taken his brain away.
One side of his brain.
But you're a proud Aggie today.
I'm a proud egghead today.
I'm sure he was too.
He was really satisfied with what happened to him here.
And I'm sure he'd have been a dean and he'd have been top of this thing yet.
About what age was he?
He was 56.
A young man.
